Well, I also have to give
credit to my good friend Graham

00:03:02.610 --> 00:03:03.410 align:middle line:90%
Hancock.

00:03:03.410 --> 00:03:10.460 align:middle line:84%
He has done as much, if not
more, and other researchers

00:03:10.460 --> 00:03:12.990 align:middle line:84%
but maybe not quite as
well known at this time.

00:03:12.990 --> 00:03:15.470 align:middle line:10%
But yes, I have been
very much trying

00:03:15.470 --> 00:03:18.740 align:middle line:10%
to get this insight
about our past history

00:03:18.740 --> 00:03:22.430 align:middle line:10%
out for going on decades now.

00:03:22.430 --> 00:03:25.310 align:middle line:10%
So anyways, if we
go back through,

00:03:25.310 --> 00:03:29.120 align:middle line:10%
like notice here if we
go back 2,160 years ago,

00:03:29.120 --> 00:03:31.700 align:middle line:10%
now we're at the cusp
of Aries, Pisces.

00:03:31.700 --> 00:03:35.570 align:middle line:84%
Go back to that little
further in about 4,320,

00:03:35.570 --> 00:03:38.520 align:middle line:84%
and we're at the cusp
of Taurus, Aries.

00:03:38.520 --> 00:03:43.230 align:middle line:84%
Go back one more, and we're
at 6,480 Before Present.

00:03:43.230 --> 00:03:46.157 align:middle line:84%
Now, here's something
very interesting.

00:03:46.157 --> 00:03:47.240 align:middle line:90%
And I'm going to show you.

00:03:47.240 --> 00:03:49.255 align:middle line:84%
Actually, we'll just
jump to the next slide.

00:03:49.255 --> 00:03:50.630 align:middle line:84%
But, first of all,
I'm just going

00:03:50.630 --> 00:03:52.310 align:middle line:84%
to call your attention
to these numbers

00:03:52.310 --> 00:03:53.840 align:middle line:84%
because these are
numbers that are

00:03:53.840 --> 00:03:56.720 align:middle line:84%
part of the sacred
canon of numerology,

00:03:56.720 --> 00:03:58.020 align:middle line:90%
if you want to call it that.

00:03:58.020 --> 00:04:00.500 align:middle line:84%
These are numbers that we
find over and over again

00:04:00.500 --> 00:04:02.480 align:middle line:84%
in the measurement
of time cycles

00:04:02.480 --> 00:04:05.760 align:middle line:84%
but also in the measurement
of geometric relationships.

00:04:05.760 --> 00:04:07.950 align:middle line:90%
Key numbers.

00:04:07.950 --> 00:04:12.080 align:middle line:84%
So if we go back right
here, 6,480 years ago,

00:04:12.080 --> 00:04:13.350 align:middle line:90%
I'll go to the next slide.

00:04:13.350 --> 00:04:17.510 align:middle line:84%
And what I've done here is
this is a very in-depth going

00:04:17.510 --> 00:04:19.100 align:middle line:84%
through the
scientific literature

00:04:19.100 --> 00:04:22.440 align:middle line:84%
cataloging what would
be catastrophic events.

00:04:22.440 --> 00:04:24.920 align:middle line:84%
My criteria that
I've used is trying

00:04:24.920 --> 00:04:29.450 align:middle line:84%
to discern events which
if they happened today

00:04:29.450 --> 00:04:34.830 align:middle line:84%
would seriously stress if not
eliminate modern civilization.

00:04:34.830 --> 00:04:37.820 align:middle line:10%
So that's the
magnitude of severity

00:04:37.820 --> 00:04:41.430 align:middle line:10%
that I used as my criteria.

00:04:41.430 --> 00:04:42.950 align:middle line:10%
And we can look
at this, and we're

00:04:42.950 --> 00:04:46.850 align:middle line:10%
going to see that there's a lot
of things arrayed around here.

00:04:46.850 --> 00:04:50.210 align:middle line:10%
Interestingly, the axis
that we're on right now

00:04:50.210 --> 00:04:53.600 align:middle line:10%
seems to be the one that's the
most prolifically represented

00:04:53.600 --> 00:04:55.790 align:middle line:10%
by catastrophic events.

00:04:55.790 --> 00:05:00.340 align:middle line:84%
You can see here, like Heinrich
event 5 happened 21,600 years

00:05:00.340 --> 00:05:01.140 align:middle line:90%
ago.

00:05:01.140 --> 00:05:02.050 align:middle line:90%
What was that?

00:05:02.050 --> 00:05:03.890 align:middle line:10%
Well, Heinrich events
are events where--

00:05:03.890 --> 00:05:06.800 align:middle line:90%


00:05:06.800 --> 00:05:08.270 align:middle line:10%
One of the things
that's been going

00:05:08.270 --> 00:05:12.470 align:middle line:10%
on since the beginning
of the Pleistocene epoch,

00:05:12.470 --> 00:05:16.470 align:middle line:10%
which goes back 2.6
million years ago,

00:05:16.470 --> 00:05:20.090 align:middle line:10%
interestingly, when you figure
that, I think maybe 2.6 million.

00:05:20.090 --> 00:05:22.310 align:middle line:10%
Well, that's 2,600,000.

00:05:22.310 --> 00:05:28.280 align:middle line:10%
Maybe it's closer to
2,580,200, something like that

00:05:28.280 --> 00:05:31.790 align:middle line:10%
because it's very, very close
to being like 100 precessional

00:05:31.790 --> 00:05:34.050 align:middle line:10%
cycles, or is it 1,000?

00:05:34.050 --> 00:05:34.890 align:middle line:90%
Doesn't matter.

00:05:34.890 --> 00:05:35.910 align:middle line:90%
You get the point.

00:05:35.910 --> 00:05:39.930 align:middle line:84%
But anyways, what happens
during a Heinrich event?

00:05:39.930 --> 00:05:40.875 align:middle line:90%
Well, if we go back--

00:05:40.875 --> 00:05:43.250 align:middle line:84%
and we're going to be talking
about this in a little more

00:05:43.250 --> 00:05:47.570 align:middle line:84%
depth-- if we go back 15,000
years, 20,000 years ago,

00:05:47.570 --> 00:05:51.380 align:middle line:84%
the world was in the
grip of a great Ice Age.

00:05:51.380 --> 00:05:52.680 align:middle line:90%
Now, what does that mean?

00:05:52.680 --> 00:05:55.097 align:middle line:84%
Well, for one thing, it means
that the average temperature

00:05:55.097 --> 00:05:57.630 align:middle line:84%
of the globe was at least
10 degrees colder than now.

00:05:57.630 --> 00:06:00.290 align:middle line:10%
It also means that there was
more than double the amount

00:06:00.290 --> 00:06:02.760 align:middle line:10%
of glacial ice that we now find.

00:06:02.760 --> 00:06:06.170 align:middle line:10%
Think about this, North
America-- more than half

00:06:06.170 --> 00:06:09.660 align:middle line:10%
of North America had a giant
ice sheet on it as big or bigger

00:06:09.660 --> 00:06:11.890 align:middle line:10%
than the one that now
covers the South Pole.

00:06:11.890 --> 00:06:15.240 align:middle line:10%
It might have been a 1 and a 1/2
to 2 miles thick over its over

00:06:15.240 --> 00:06:17.500 align:middle line:10%
its core over Central Canada.

00:06:17.500 --> 00:06:19.620 align:middle line:10%
It reached from the
Atlantic to the Pacific

00:06:19.620 --> 00:06:24.390 align:middle line:10%
and from the Northern United
States up to the Arctic Circle.

00:06:24.390 --> 00:06:28.540 align:middle line:10%
Northern cities like New York,
Boston, Philadelphia, Detroit,

00:06:28.540 --> 00:06:34.030 align:middle line:10%
Chicago, Milwaukee, The Twin
Cities, Seattle, Portland,

00:06:34.030 --> 00:06:37.360 align:middle line:10%
they were all buried under
thousands of feet of ice.

00:06:37.360 --> 00:06:41.540 align:middle line:10%
Now, in a geological frame,
this is no time at all.

00:06:41.540 --> 00:06:45.620 align:middle line:10%
Now, obviously, there were
people living on the planet

00:06:45.620 --> 00:06:47.070 align:middle line:10%
during that Ice Age.

00:06:47.070 --> 00:06:50.030 align:middle line:84%
And, to this day,
I have challenged

00:06:50.030 --> 00:06:52.940 align:middle line:84%
many proponents of
the climate crisis

00:06:52.940 --> 00:06:55.790 align:middle line:90%
that we're supposedly now in.

00:06:55.790 --> 00:06:58.370 align:middle line:10%
I've challenged them
to explain to me, OK,

00:06:58.370 --> 00:07:00.980 align:middle line:10%
given that the
science is settled

00:07:00.980 --> 00:07:05.780 align:middle line:10%
and there is a consensus about
what drives climate change,

00:07:05.780 --> 00:07:09.020 align:middle line:10%
let's look at some of the
most extreme climate changes

00:07:09.020 --> 00:07:10.230 align:middle line:10%
that we can document.

00:07:10.230 --> 00:07:13.310 align:middle line:10%
And this is the transition
into and out of a glacial age.

00:07:13.310 --> 00:07:15.170 align:middle line:10%
What's going on there?

00:07:15.170 --> 00:07:18.090 align:middle line:10%
Nobody can explain it
because it's still a mystery.

00:07:18.090 --> 00:07:20.720 align:middle line:10%
And the problem is
there were models,

00:07:20.720 --> 00:07:22.380 align:middle line:10%
but how do you get
out of an Ice Age?

00:07:22.380 --> 00:07:26.210 align:middle line:10%
Well, Milenkovic forces,
which are very slow,

00:07:26.210 --> 00:07:29.540 align:middle line:10%
which would require tens
of thousands of years.

00:07:29.540 --> 00:07:33.180 align:middle line:10%
50,000, 60,000, 70,000 years,
those were the old models.

00:07:33.180 --> 00:07:36.800 align:middle line:10%
But now with much improved
dating and precision,

00:07:36.800 --> 00:07:40.550 align:middle line:10%
we can say that, yeah, most of
that ice was gone in three major

00:07:40.550 --> 00:07:44.900 align:middle line:10%
pulses in about 3,000 years.

00:07:44.900 --> 00:07:46.250 align:middle line:10%
How do you explain that?

00:07:46.250 --> 00:07:49.730 align:middle line:10%
In fact, this was realized in
the early '70s by scientists who

00:07:49.730 --> 00:07:53.330 align:middle line:10%
were looking at the rapidity
with which the ice came

00:07:53.330 --> 00:07:56.630 align:middle line:10%
and left, and they ended
up scratching their heads.

00:07:56.630 --> 00:08:01.280 align:middle line:10%
They coined the
term energy paradox.

00:08:01.280 --> 00:08:04.860 align:middle line:10%
Because, obviously, if you've
got 6,000,000 or 7,000,000

00:08:04.860 --> 00:08:07.760 align:middle line:10%
million cubic miles of ice
piled up on the continents,

00:08:07.760 --> 00:08:09.480 align:middle line:10%
there's another
consequence of that.

00:08:09.480 --> 00:08:12.590 align:middle line:10%
One is that that's,
ultimately, seawater

00:08:12.590 --> 00:08:14.630 align:middle line:10%
that's been evaporated
out of the oceans,

00:08:14.630 --> 00:08:17.100 align:middle line:10%
precipitated out, and
then never melted.

00:08:17.100 --> 00:08:19.280 align:middle line:90%
It just piled up as glacial ice.

00:08:19.280 --> 00:08:21.030 align:middle line:90%
Sea levels dropped.

00:08:21.030 --> 00:08:23.480 align:middle line:10%
So during the late
glacial maximum,

00:08:23.480 --> 00:08:26.300 align:middle line:10%
if we go back 14,000
to 20,000 years ago,

00:08:26.300 --> 00:08:30.710 align:middle line:10%
sea levels are 400 feet
lower than now, 400.

00:08:30.710 --> 00:08:32.039 align:middle line:90%
Now, what did that mean?

00:08:32.039 --> 00:08:35.840 align:middle line:84%
Well, what it did was it
exposed the continental shelves

00:08:35.840 --> 00:08:37.909 align:middle line:90%
of every continent on Earth.

00:08:37.909 --> 00:08:42.140 align:middle line:10%
And about as much land was
reclaimed by the dropping

00:08:42.140 --> 00:08:45.900 align:middle line:10%
of sea level as was lost
because it was swallowed up

00:08:45.900 --> 00:08:47.930 align:middle line:10%
under glacial ice.

00:08:47.930 --> 00:08:52.820 align:middle line:10%
Now, during ice ages,
the most benign place

00:08:52.820 --> 00:08:55.130 align:middle line:10%
that you're going to try
to establish a settlement

00:08:55.130 --> 00:09:00.120 align:middle line:10%
or a colony or even a city
would be along coastlines.

00:09:00.120 --> 00:09:02.600 align:middle line:10%
Well, those coastlines are
under 400 feet of water now.

00:09:02.600 --> 00:09:04.713 align:middle line:10%
This is why I say that
the future of archaeology

00:09:04.713 --> 00:09:06.380 align:middle line:10%
is probably going to
be under the oceans

00:09:06.380 --> 00:09:08.630 align:middle line:10%
because we're just beginning
to realize that there was

00:09:08.630 --> 00:09:11.600 align:middle line:10%
a whole lot of stuff going
on those exposed continental

00:09:11.600 --> 00:09:12.530 align:middle line:10%
shelves.

00:09:12.530 --> 00:09:16.010 align:middle line:10%
But now we have this pulse
where the glaciers have grown.

00:09:16.010 --> 00:09:17.090 align:middle line:10%
They've shrunk away.

00:09:17.090 --> 00:09:18.060 align:middle line:10%
Sea level goes down.

00:09:18.060 --> 00:09:18.860 align:middle line:10%
It comes up.

00:09:18.860 --> 00:09:20.110 align:middle line:10%
It goes down, and it comes up.

00:09:20.110 --> 00:09:22.730 align:middle line:10%
And it's probably done this
a couple of dozen times,

00:09:22.730 --> 00:09:26.210 align:middle line:10%
perhaps throughout the course
of the Pleistocene, which,

00:09:26.210 --> 00:09:28.590 align:middle line:10%
like I said, goes back
2.6 million years.

00:09:28.590 --> 00:09:33.180 align:middle line:10%
Now, we have epochs in
geological timekeeping.

00:09:33.180 --> 00:09:36.500 align:middle line:10%
And then the Pleistocene
was an epoch.

00:09:36.500 --> 00:09:39.350 align:middle line:10%
And the Holocene, which is
the period we're in now,

00:09:39.350 --> 00:09:40.880 align:middle line:10%
is also an epoch.

00:09:40.880 --> 00:09:45.890 align:middle line:10%
Well, the current length of the
Holocene is given as 11,600.

00:09:45.890 --> 00:09:48.060 align:middle line:10%
So this raises an
interesting question,

00:09:48.060 --> 00:09:50.880 align:middle line:10%
is the Holocene really
a completely separate

00:09:50.880 --> 00:09:54.000 align:middle line:10%
geological epoch different
from the Pleistocene,

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:56.880 align:middle line:10%
or is it simply
another variation

00:09:56.880 --> 00:09:58.540 align:middle line:10%
within the Pleistocene itself?

00:09:58.540 --> 00:10:01.800 align:middle line:10%
Now, what characterizes the
Pleistocene from the preceding

00:10:01.800 --> 00:10:06.450 align:middle line:10%
epoch, the Pliocene, is that
there was a major climatic shift

00:10:06.450 --> 00:10:08.940 align:middle line:10%
right at 2.6 million years ago.

00:10:08.940 --> 00:10:12.630 align:middle line:10%
And this is when we begin to see
this oscillation of the planet

00:10:12.630 --> 00:10:14.700 align:middle line:10%
between glacial and
interglacial ages,

00:10:14.700 --> 00:10:16.420 align:middle line:10%
back and forth, back and forth.

00:10:16.420 --> 00:10:18.840 align:middle line:10%
And that's what defines
and distinguishes

00:10:18.840 --> 00:10:22.080 align:middle line:10%
the Pleistocene from the
previous rather steady state

00:10:22.080 --> 00:10:25.100 align:middle line:10%
warm condition of the Pliocene.

00:10:25.100 --> 00:10:28.740 align:middle line:10%
So the question in my mind
is, is the Holocene really

00:10:28.740 --> 00:10:32.130 align:middle line:10%
a distinct geological
epoch, or is it just

00:10:32.130 --> 00:10:36.192 align:middle line:10%
a sub epoch within
the Pleistocene?

00:10:36.192 --> 00:10:37.650 align:middle line:10%
Well, here's the
interesting thing,

00:10:37.650 --> 00:10:43.080 align:middle line:10%
with our high-resolution
reconstructions of climate

00:10:43.080 --> 00:10:45.390 align:middle line:10%
now going back a quarter
of a million years

00:10:45.390 --> 00:10:51.780 align:middle line:10%
based upon ever-improving
dating technologies,

00:10:51.780 --> 00:10:55.410 align:middle line:10%
we can see that within the
last quarter million years,

00:10:55.410 --> 00:10:59.790 align:middle line:10%
there have been maybe four
cycles, glacial, interglacial.

00:10:59.790 --> 00:11:02.460 align:middle line:10%
And the interglacial
like that we're in now,

00:11:02.460 --> 00:11:05.310 align:middle line:10%
the Holocene, when we
look at the duration

00:11:05.310 --> 00:11:07.410 align:middle line:10%
of the previous
ones, we've already

00:11:07.410 --> 00:11:11.400 align:middle line:10%
outlasted the previous ones
by a couple of thousand years.

00:11:11.400 --> 00:11:12.490 align:middle line:10%
What does that mean?

00:11:12.490 --> 00:11:16.020 align:middle line:10%
Well, I don't know, other than
the fact that if the duration

00:11:16.020 --> 00:11:19.710 align:middle line:10%
of an interglacial is
8,000 or 10,000 years,

00:11:19.710 --> 00:11:22.370 align:middle line:10%
we're going on 11,600 years now.

00:11:22.370 --> 00:11:28.080 align:middle line:84%
11,600 years is the date now
given to the transition between

00:11:28.080 --> 00:11:29.790 align:middle line:90%
Pleistocene and Holocene.

00:11:29.790 --> 00:11:33.100 align:middle line:10%
That date to me, it was
always really interesting.

00:11:33.100 --> 00:11:33.900 align:middle line:10%
Why?

00:11:33.900 --> 00:11:38.520 align:middle line:10%
Because even before that
date was honed in on back

00:11:38.520 --> 00:11:41.730 align:middle line:10%
in the '70s when I first started
reading Plato and reading about

00:11:41.730 --> 00:11:46.170 align:middle line:10%
Atlantis, I learned that the
Egyptian priests told Solon that

00:11:46.170 --> 00:11:51.360 align:middle line:10%
Atlantis subsided 9,000 years
before Solon's journey to Egypt,

00:11:51.360 --> 00:11:54.650 align:middle line:10%
which occurred 2,600 years ago.

00:11:54.650 --> 00:11:57.740 align:middle line:10%
So, in other words, Plato
is telling us that something

00:11:57.740 --> 00:12:02.910 align:middle line:10%
happened, a major catastrophe
happened 11,600 years ago.

00:12:02.910 --> 00:12:07.940 align:middle line:10%
And we now know that is the
upper, Younger Dryas boundary.

00:12:07.940 --> 00:12:13.100 align:middle line:10%
The Younger Dryas period lasted
from right at 12,900 to 11,600

00:12:13.100 --> 00:12:15.450 align:middle line:10%
years ago, about 1,300 years.

00:12:15.450 --> 00:12:21.080 align:middle line:10%
And it was associated with what
is called meltwater pulse 1B.

00:12:21.080 --> 00:12:25.040 align:middle line:10%
In other words, marine
geologists and oceanographers

00:12:25.040 --> 00:12:28.700 align:middle line:10%
have identified a point in
time where over very short

00:12:28.700 --> 00:12:32.040 align:middle line:10%
duration sea levels
massively rose.

00:12:32.040 --> 00:12:34.250 align:middle line:10%
In other words, the
rising of the sea levels

00:12:34.250 --> 00:12:37.460 align:middle line:10%
from 400 feet lower
to the present level

00:12:37.460 --> 00:12:39.030 align:middle line:10%
didn't happen smooth.

00:12:39.030 --> 00:12:42.680 align:middle line:10%
It happened in a series of
tremendous, powerful pulses

00:12:42.680 --> 00:12:44.400 align:middle line:10%
of meltwater.

00:12:44.400 --> 00:12:49.020 align:middle line:84%
So this is where I think the
origins of the Great Flood

00:12:49.020 --> 00:12:50.890 align:middle line:90%
myths, ultimately, came from.

00:12:50.890 --> 00:12:53.280 align:middle line:84%
And one of the things
that I would mention

00:12:53.280 --> 00:12:58.020 align:middle line:84%
is that I see that there are
three possible mechanisms

00:12:58.020 --> 00:13:02.380 align:middle line:84%
by which you could produce
catastrophic floods.

00:13:02.380 --> 00:13:09.580 align:middle line:10%
One is the rapidly melting
ice sheets of the glaciers.

00:13:09.580 --> 00:13:13.900 align:middle line:10%
Then you would also have
the corresponding rapid rise

00:13:13.900 --> 00:13:15.160 align:middle line:10%
of sea level.

00:13:15.160 --> 00:13:20.260 align:middle line:84%
The other is that there
would be tremendous prolonged

00:13:20.260 --> 00:13:22.450 align:middle line:90%
torrential rain falls.

00:13:22.450 --> 00:13:25.820 align:middle line:10%
And I'll get into it in a second
what could provoke such a thing.

00:13:25.820 --> 00:13:29.500 align:middle line:10%
And the third is now
the newly emerging

00:13:29.500 --> 00:13:33.310 align:middle line:10%
or consistently emerging new
evidence for gigantic tsunamis

00:13:33.310 --> 00:13:36.040 align:middle line:10%
that have swept over the
coastlines of the planet

00:13:36.040 --> 00:13:37.190 align:middle line:10%
from time to time.

00:13:37.190 --> 00:13:40.492 align:middle line:10%
And I'm talking about tsunamis
that many of you are aware of.

00:13:40.492 --> 00:13:41.950 align:middle line:10%
There are a couple
of tsunamis that

00:13:41.950 --> 00:13:44.320 align:middle line:10%
had happened to
Japan and Indonesia

00:13:44.320 --> 00:13:45.770 align:middle line:10%
in the last few decades.

00:13:45.770 --> 00:13:48.410 align:middle line:10%
I'm talking about tsunamis
that would dwarf those.

00:13:48.410 --> 00:13:50.390 align:middle line:10%
We now know that
those have happened.

00:13:50.390 --> 00:13:54.620 align:middle line:10%
We can find the evidence of
those events having occurred.

00:13:54.620 --> 00:14:01.200 align:middle line:10%
Now, referring back to this
idea of the energy paradox,

00:14:01.200 --> 00:14:04.020 align:middle line:10%
what that means is that if
you're going to try to get rid

00:14:04.020 --> 00:14:07.110 align:middle line:10%
of 6,000,000 million cubic miles
of glacial ice in a few thousand

00:14:07.110 --> 00:14:09.550 align:middle line:10%
years, you've got to
have a lot of energy.

00:14:09.550 --> 00:14:11.840 align:middle line:10%
And where's that
energy coming from?

00:14:11.840 --> 00:14:13.940 align:middle line:10%
This was the paradox.

00:14:13.940 --> 00:14:19.480 align:middle line:10%
And there was some calculations
done saying, well, if you used--

00:14:19.480 --> 00:14:22.870 align:middle line:10%
it was assumed that the
primary source of such energy

00:14:22.870 --> 00:14:26.300 align:middle line:10%
would have to be the
sun, solar irradiation.

00:14:26.300 --> 00:14:28.730 align:middle line:10%
So what they did was
they started looking.

00:14:28.730 --> 00:14:31.090 align:middle line:10%
The geographers came
in and started looking.

00:14:31.090 --> 00:14:34.480 align:middle line:10%
The solar sciences started
looking, well, where on Earth

00:14:34.480 --> 00:14:39.460 align:middle line:10%
would you have the greatest
availability of solar irradiance

00:14:39.460 --> 00:14:40.460 align:middle line:10%
to melt ice?

00:14:40.460 --> 00:14:42.560 align:middle line:10%
And it turned out to
be tropical oceans.

00:14:42.560 --> 00:14:44.950 align:middle line:10%
Well, then this is where the
paradox came in because they

00:14:44.950 --> 00:14:46.670 align:middle line:10%
didn't do their calculations.

00:14:46.670 --> 00:14:50.870 align:middle line:10%
They said, well, if you took the
entire mass of ice over North

00:14:50.870 --> 00:14:54.320 align:middle line:10%
America and moved it
to the tropical oceans,

00:14:54.320 --> 00:14:57.050 align:middle line:10%
it would still take 20,000 to
30,000 years to melt the whole

00:14:57.050 --> 00:14:58.240 align:middle line:10%
thing.

00:14:58.240 --> 00:14:59.490 align:middle line:10%
So where does that leave us?

00:14:59.490 --> 00:15:01.490 align:middle line:10%
Well, this is the
energy paradox.

00:15:01.490 --> 00:15:04.930 align:middle line:10%
And so in order to
explain this, we

00:15:04.930 --> 00:15:09.070 align:middle line:10%
have to come up with a
source of inconceivable

00:15:09.070 --> 00:15:10.780 align:middle line:10%
magnitude of energy.

00:15:10.780 --> 00:15:13.930 align:middle line:10%
And I think there are
two potential sources.

00:15:13.930 --> 00:15:18.010 align:middle line:10%
One is direct impacts
into the oceans and ice

00:15:18.010 --> 00:15:21.700 align:middle line:10%
sheets of fragmented
cosmic bodies

00:15:21.700 --> 00:15:23.680 align:middle line:10%
like asteroids and comets.

00:15:23.680 --> 00:15:26.200 align:middle line:10%
And the other would be
tremendously powerful

00:15:26.200 --> 00:15:27.640 align:middle line:10%
solar storms.

00:15:27.640 --> 00:15:30.640 align:middle line:10%
There has been a recent paper
just published that puts

00:15:30.640 --> 00:15:35.230 align:middle line:10%
meltwater pulse 1A at the very
same time there appears to have

00:15:35.230 --> 00:15:37.500 align:middle line:10%
been a gigantic solar storm.

00:15:37.500 --> 00:15:40.950 align:middle line:10%
This is now dated
to around 14,300--

00:15:40.950 --> 00:15:43.080 align:middle line:10%
to 14,400 years ago.

00:15:43.080 --> 00:15:45.190 align:middle line:84%
How many of you heard
of the Carrington Event?

00:15:45.190 --> 00:15:48.600 align:middle line:84%
Happened in the 1800s, and it
was just after telegraphs had

00:15:48.600 --> 00:15:49.400 align:middle line:90%
been in place.

00:15:49.400 --> 00:15:52.480 align:middle line:84%
And I mean, it basically
blew out the telegraphs.

00:15:52.480 --> 00:15:54.700 align:middle line:84%
And now the Carrington
Event, what we now know

00:15:54.700 --> 00:15:58.510 align:middle line:84%
is that is a relatively
mild solar event.

00:15:58.510 --> 00:16:04.090 align:middle line:10%
This is another variable in this
equation of life on Earth that

00:16:04.090 --> 00:16:07.480 align:middle line:10%
we at some point in the long
range planning need to account

00:16:07.480 --> 00:16:12.670 align:middle line:10%
for the fact that unlike the
models of solar change that were

00:16:12.670 --> 00:16:17.410 align:middle line:10%
in place when, say, the first
climate models began to be

00:16:17.410 --> 00:16:21.100 align:middle line:10%
developed in late '80s and '90s
that led to the global warming

00:16:21.100 --> 00:16:25.420 align:middle line:10%
scenario, the interpretation
of the sun was expressed

00:16:25.420 --> 00:16:27.780 align:middle line:10%
in the term solar constant.

00:16:27.780 --> 00:16:31.090 align:middle line:10%
So in that model
of the sun, the sun

00:16:31.090 --> 00:16:34.240 align:middle line:10%
never changed enough to
really warrant being included

00:16:34.240 --> 00:16:35.840 align:middle line:10%
in the computer models.

00:16:35.840 --> 00:16:40.300 align:middle line:10%
Well, since then now we've
deployed a whole generation

00:16:40.300 --> 00:16:42.240 align:middle line:10%
of solar observing satellites.

00:16:42.240 --> 00:16:47.020 align:middle line:10%
We're also finding and observing
the activity of sun-like stars

00:16:47.020 --> 00:16:48.130 align:middle line:10%
nearby.

00:16:48.130 --> 00:16:51.490 align:middle line:10%
And what is leading us
to is the realization

00:16:51.490 --> 00:16:54.670 align:middle line:10%
that, yes, the
sun does sometimes

00:16:54.670 --> 00:16:56.890 align:middle line:10%
go through cyclical changes.

00:16:56.890 --> 00:17:01.010 align:middle line:10%
That it's not a solar
constant, that there

00:17:01.010 --> 00:17:03.092 align:middle line:10%
are tremendous
variations in the sun.

00:17:03.092 --> 00:17:04.550 align:middle line:10%
There's some new
research that I've

00:17:04.550 --> 00:17:07.040 align:middle line:10%
been exploring that
suggests there's

00:17:07.040 --> 00:17:11.089 align:middle line:10%
a relationship to the
infall of cometary masses

00:17:11.089 --> 00:17:14.033 align:middle line:10%
into the chromosphere that can
actually trigger solar storms.

00:17:14.033 --> 00:17:15.950 align:middle line:10%
I'm not going to get
into that too much today,

00:17:15.950 --> 00:17:18.500 align:middle line:10%
but I do talk about
that a lot in my podcast

00:17:18.500 --> 00:17:20.420 align:middle line:10%
and show the data, and so on.

00:17:20.420 --> 00:17:22.849 align:middle line:10%
So anyways, the Heinrich event--

00:17:22.849 --> 00:17:27.859 align:middle line:10%
what happens is they are these
periodic occurrences where

00:17:27.859 --> 00:17:32.300 align:middle line:10%
large masses of ice are
disgorged into the oceans,

00:17:32.300 --> 00:17:36.560 align:middle line:10%
primarily, coming from
the ice over Canada

00:17:36.560 --> 00:17:38.350 align:middle line:10%
and over Northwestern Europe.

00:17:38.350 --> 00:17:41.630 align:middle line:10%
It's almost as if there's
a gigantic breakup of ice,

00:17:41.630 --> 00:17:45.470 align:middle line:10%
and you have armadas of
thousands of icebergs disgorging

00:17:45.470 --> 00:17:46.770 align:middle line:10%
into the ocean.

00:17:46.770 --> 00:17:49.160 align:middle line:10%
Those icebergs then drift south.

00:17:49.160 --> 00:17:51.570 align:middle line:10%
And those icebergs
were glacial ice.

00:17:51.570 --> 00:17:53.690 align:middle line:10%
So when the glaciers are
moving over the land,

00:17:53.690 --> 00:17:57.560 align:middle line:10%
they're scooping up material,
the bedrock and the soil

00:17:57.560 --> 00:18:00.140 align:middle line:10%
and all of this stuff,
gravel, pulverizing it.

00:18:00.140 --> 00:18:02.730 align:middle line:10%
And that gets incorporated
into the glacial ice.

00:18:02.730 --> 00:18:05.450 align:middle line:10%
Then when the glacial ice
migrates to the coast.

00:18:05.450 --> 00:18:09.020 align:middle line:10%
And in that whatever it is that
triggers these Heinrich events,

00:18:09.020 --> 00:18:12.020 align:middle line:10%
you have this massive
convulsion of icebergs

00:18:12.020 --> 00:18:13.650 align:middle line:10%
discharging into the ocean.

00:18:13.650 --> 00:18:14.690 align:middle line:10%
They drift south.

00:18:14.690 --> 00:18:17.600 align:middle line:10%
And when they do this, they
begin to melt. And as they melt,

00:18:17.600 --> 00:18:21.410 align:middle line:10%
their cargo of gravel
and coarse material

00:18:21.410 --> 00:18:25.620 align:middle line:10%
falls to the ocean floor and
leaves very distinct layers.

00:18:25.620 --> 00:18:27.300 align:middle line:10%
And those can be dated.

00:18:27.300 --> 00:18:30.530 align:middle line:10%
And so from this
kind of evidence,

00:18:30.530 --> 00:18:34.570 align:middle line:10%
we can now begin to reconstruct
the ancient climate.

00:18:34.570 --> 00:18:36.820 align:middle line:10%
Before moving on, I'm just
going to show you one more.

00:18:36.820 --> 00:18:38.970 align:middle line:10%
Here's a great little depiction.

00:18:38.970 --> 00:18:41.840 align:middle line:10%
This is the Chalice Well
lid at Glastonbury Abbey.

00:18:41.840 --> 00:18:45.410 align:middle line:10%
And it shows a perfect
depiction of the Vesica Piscis.

00:18:45.410 --> 00:18:47.960 align:middle line:84%
And it connects it
directly with the idea

00:18:47.960 --> 00:18:52.640 align:middle line:84%
of the Holy Grail, which is
something that I also lecture on

00:18:52.640 --> 00:18:54.830 align:middle line:84%
because I think that
the Grail literature was

00:18:54.830 --> 00:18:59.945 align:middle line:84%
a vehicle for transmitting a lot
of really crucial information.

00:18:59.945 --> 00:19:01.820 align:middle line:10%
And if you know about
the quest of the Grail,

00:19:01.820 --> 00:19:04.130 align:middle line:10%
you understand that--

00:19:04.130 --> 00:19:06.480 align:middle line:10%
well, what was the
secret of the Grail?

00:19:06.480 --> 00:19:09.890 align:middle line:10%
Anybody can tell me, what
is the secret of the Grail?

00:19:09.890 --> 00:19:14.190 align:middle line:84%
It was that the king
and the land are one.

00:19:14.190 --> 00:19:14.990 align:middle line:90%
That was it.

00:19:14.990 --> 00:19:16.810 align:middle line:10%
And remember, if you
read the stories--

00:19:16.810 --> 00:19:20.110 align:middle line:10%
and I cannot recommend
highly enough reading some

00:19:20.110 --> 00:19:22.460 align:middle line:10%
of the stories by--
there are translations--

00:19:22.460 --> 00:19:26.290 align:middle line:10%
Wolfram von Eschenbach, Chrétien
de Troyes, Robert de Boron,

00:19:26.290 --> 00:19:28.940 align:middle line:10%
and the anonymous
author of "Parlez Vous."

00:19:28.940 --> 00:19:31.180 align:middle line:10%
This makes some
extraordinary reading.

00:19:31.180 --> 00:19:33.910 align:middle line:10%
But what you find there,
the quest of the Grail

00:19:33.910 --> 00:19:36.100 align:middle line:10%
was about the Grail
was the antidote

00:19:36.100 --> 00:19:39.880 align:middle line:10%
to the debilitating ailment
that the king was suffering

00:19:39.880 --> 00:19:46.030 align:middle line:10%
simultaneously with the land
around which had degenerated

00:19:46.030 --> 00:19:47.450 align:middle line:10%
into a wasteland.

00:19:47.450 --> 00:19:50.650 align:middle line:10%
And so the Grail
was the antidote

00:19:50.650 --> 00:19:54.320 align:middle line:10%
not only to the ailing
king but the ailing land.

00:19:54.320 --> 00:19:57.550 align:middle line:10%
And the recovery of the Grail
would not only restore the king,

00:19:57.550 --> 00:19:59.710 align:middle line:10%
but it would restore
the land as well,

00:19:59.710 --> 00:20:01.550 align:middle line:10%
that it would restore
the wasteland.

00:20:01.550 --> 00:20:03.970 align:middle line:10%
Well, interestingly, we
can look at things now,

00:20:03.970 --> 00:20:08.680 align:middle line:10%
and we know that the Arthurian
tales were centered right

00:20:08.680 --> 00:20:12.330 align:middle line:10%
around the year 540 AD.

00:20:12.330 --> 00:20:15.170 align:middle line:10%
In fact, the famous
battle of Camlann,

00:20:15.170 --> 00:20:22.640 align:middle line:10%
where Arthur fought to
death his son, Mordred,

00:20:22.640 --> 00:20:25.940 align:middle line:10%
is usually dated at 540 AD.

00:20:25.940 --> 00:20:32.630 align:middle line:10%
Well, six years from 536 to 542
AD were the four coldest years

00:20:32.630 --> 00:20:36.020 align:middle line:10%
of the last 2,000 years,
were the six coldest years

00:20:36.020 --> 00:20:38.386 align:middle line:10%
of the last 2,000.

00:20:38.386 --> 00:20:43.160 align:middle line:10%
536 AD was the single coldest
year of the last 2,000 years.

00:20:43.160 --> 00:20:47.600 align:middle line:10%
Subsequent to 536 AD,
for the next 10 years,

00:20:47.600 --> 00:20:50.390 align:middle line:10%
forest growth almost
came to a screeching halt

00:20:50.390 --> 00:20:51.720 align:middle line:10%
over the northern hemisphere.

00:20:51.720 --> 00:20:54.960 align:middle line:10%
Something major occurred
in the global climate.

00:20:54.960 --> 00:20:58.820 align:middle line:10%
It caused global cooling,
and literally, it

00:20:58.820 --> 00:21:01.400 align:middle line:10%
rendered the landscape of
the northern hemisphere

00:21:01.400 --> 00:21:04.530 align:middle line:10%
over large region into
a literal wasteland.

00:21:04.530 --> 00:21:07.790 align:middle line:10%
So we now know that there's this
correlation between something

00:21:07.790 --> 00:21:10.400 align:middle line:10%
that's been well documented
now through tree ring

00:21:10.400 --> 00:21:12.590 align:middle line:10%
records and all kinds
of other evidence

00:21:12.590 --> 00:21:15.740 align:middle line:10%
that fits precisely in
with the Grail stories.

00:21:15.740 --> 00:21:19.280 align:middle line:10%
So right there, I find
that that correlation

00:21:19.280 --> 00:21:21.120 align:middle line:10%
is profoundly important.

00:21:21.120 --> 00:21:23.900 align:middle line:10%
And it means that in
the Grail literature,

00:21:23.900 --> 00:21:28.640 align:middle line:10%
which all came out between
roughly 1,180 and 1,230,

00:21:28.640 --> 00:21:32.420 align:middle line:10%
in there in about a half a
century is dealing with that

00:21:32.420 --> 00:21:36.380 align:middle line:10%
epoch and has used that
epoch as a symbolical vehicle

00:21:36.380 --> 00:21:39.350 align:middle line:10%
for the transmission
of certain information.

00:21:39.350 --> 00:21:42.080 align:middle line:84%
Somebody over here said energy,
and I would agree with that.

00:21:42.080 --> 00:21:43.850 align:middle line:10%
Because I think
what we're actually

00:21:43.850 --> 00:21:46.430 align:middle line:10%
dealing with here in
the Grail literature

00:21:46.430 --> 00:21:50.420 align:middle line:10%
is a way of symbolically
encoding information

00:21:50.420 --> 00:21:52.888 align:middle line:10%
about a lost technology.

00:21:52.888 --> 00:21:54.930 align:middle line:10%
Hopefully, we'll have some
time to get into that,

00:21:54.930 --> 00:21:56.300 align:middle line:10%
but let's keep going.

