This was 1979 "From the
viewpoint of the climatologist,

00:33:14.320 --> 00:33:16.530 align:middle line:84%
the most important result
of these investigations

00:33:16.530 --> 00:33:18.930 align:middle line:84%
is the fact that within the
human timescale of about

00:33:18.930 --> 00:33:22.920 align:middle line:84%
100 years or less, our
climate is much more

00:33:22.920 --> 00:33:25.080 align:middle line:90%
variable than hitherto assumed.

00:33:25.080 --> 00:33:27.540 align:middle line:84%
Especially important,
and indeed disquieting,

00:33:27.540 --> 00:33:30.330 align:middle line:84%
is the evidence of abrupt
coolings within warm

00:33:30.330 --> 00:33:33.870 align:middle line:84%
interglacial periods, apparently
as rare events with a recurrence

00:33:33.870 --> 00:33:35.730 align:middle line:90%
interval of 10,000 years."

00:33:35.730 --> 00:33:40.210 align:middle line:10%
Remember, I said, we're in the
current Holocene is 11,600.

00:33:40.210 --> 00:33:43.170 align:middle line:10%
So we've already gone
beyond any previous

00:33:43.170 --> 00:33:45.600 align:middle line:10%
by a millennia or two
any previous period

00:33:45.600 --> 00:33:47.967 align:middle line:10%
of comparable warmth.

00:33:47.967 --> 00:33:49.800 align:middle line:84%
And then he goes on to
say that "The problem

00:33:49.800 --> 00:33:53.230 align:middle line:84%
of abrupt intense cooling
during the interglacial climate

00:33:53.230 --> 00:33:56.350 align:middle line:84%
similar to the present climate
resembles, to some extent,

00:33:56.350 --> 00:33:59.170 align:middle line:84%
the Damocles' sword hanging
high above the globe

00:33:59.170 --> 00:34:00.460 align:middle line:90%
and its inhabitants.

00:34:00.460 --> 00:34:03.410 align:middle line:84%
Because of its possible
consequence for the human race,

00:34:03.410 --> 00:34:06.400 align:middle line:84%
its study deserves a
much higher priority."

00:34:06.400 --> 00:34:10.003 align:middle line:10%
I read this paper when it came
out in 1979 and then in 1980

00:34:10.003 --> 00:34:11.920 align:middle line:10%
when I heard that the
United Nations Framework

00:34:11.920 --> 00:34:15.310 align:middle line:10%
Convention on Climate Change
was going to establish the IPCC

00:34:15.310 --> 00:34:19.120 align:middle line:10%
to study climate change
at much deeper, in greater

00:34:19.120 --> 00:34:22.120 align:middle line:10%
depth and detail, I
thought, yes, we need that.

00:34:22.120 --> 00:34:24.290 align:middle line:10%
We need to know what's
going on with this.

00:34:24.290 --> 00:34:26.500 align:middle line:10%
Well, you can
understand, I hope,

00:34:26.500 --> 00:34:29.530 align:middle line:10%
why I was dismayed when I
realized that this was not

00:34:29.530 --> 00:34:30.710 align:middle line:10%
going to be about science.

00:34:30.710 --> 00:34:32.960 align:middle line:10%
This was actually a
political institution.

00:34:32.960 --> 00:34:36.230 align:middle line:10%
And they had a preset agenda,
which is easily demonstrable.

00:34:36.230 --> 00:34:38.889 align:middle line:10%
They had a preset
agenda to demonstrate

00:34:38.889 --> 00:34:42.800 align:middle line:10%
the anthropogenic component
exclusively on climate change.

00:34:42.800 --> 00:34:45.520 align:middle line:10%
And basically, the
stuff that Hermann Flohn

00:34:45.520 --> 00:34:47.770 align:middle line:10%
is saying that we really
need to be studying

00:34:47.770 --> 00:34:50.690 align:middle line:10%
got shunted off to the side.

00:34:50.690 --> 00:34:53.670 align:middle line:84%
Most people don't know
this, and it's important

00:34:53.670 --> 00:34:54.610 align:middle line:90%
that we do know this.

00:34:54.610 --> 00:34:58.210 align:middle line:84%
And here's something that
I think may even shock you.

00:34:58.210 --> 00:34:59.860 align:middle line:90%
This is the last 10,000 years.

00:34:59.860 --> 00:35:01.843 align:middle line:90%
This is based upon ice cores.

00:35:01.843 --> 00:35:04.260 align:middle line:84%
What this showing here, the
graph of the last 10,000 years

00:35:04.260 --> 00:35:06.990 align:middle line:84%
of temperature change is
preserved in Greenland ice cores

00:35:06.990 --> 00:35:10.740 align:middle line:84%
shows temperature and constantly
and repeatedly warming

00:35:10.740 --> 00:35:13.420 align:middle line:84%
and cooling 2 to 3
Fahrenheit or more.

00:35:13.420 --> 00:35:16.630 align:middle line:84%
So what you're seeing
here is not a smooth line.

00:35:16.630 --> 00:35:17.980 align:middle line:90%
It's a jagged line.

00:35:17.980 --> 00:35:20.590 align:middle line:84%
It's constantly upping
and downing as much as 2

00:35:20.590 --> 00:35:22.200 align:middle line:90%
to 3 degrees.

00:35:22.200 --> 00:35:24.250 align:middle line:10%
Colder, warmer, colder, warmer.

00:35:24.250 --> 00:35:29.530 align:middle line:10%
And this we can see reflected in
many proxies from the Holocene.

00:35:29.530 --> 00:35:31.360 align:middle line:10%
And here's where it
gets interesting.

00:35:31.360 --> 00:35:36.227 align:middle line:10%
If we go back beyond the
Holocene into the Pleistocene,

00:35:36.227 --> 00:35:38.060 align:middle line:10%
now bear in mind what
we're looking at here.

00:35:38.060 --> 00:35:40.268 align:middle line:84%
If you look at this closely,
you'll see, for example,

00:35:40.268 --> 00:35:42.200 align:middle line:84%
there's a spike of
cold right here.

00:35:42.200 --> 00:35:45.910 align:middle line:84%
That spike of cold would be
enough to pretty much terminate

00:35:45.910 --> 00:35:48.260 align:middle line:84%
modern civilization
as we know it.

00:35:48.260 --> 00:35:49.060 align:middle line:90%
Why?

00:35:49.060 --> 00:35:53.190 align:middle line:84%
Because that spike of cold was
3 or 4 degrees colder than now.

00:35:53.190 --> 00:35:54.990 align:middle line:90%
It lasted for several years.

00:35:54.990 --> 00:35:56.740 align:middle line:10%
If something like that
were to happen now,

00:35:56.740 --> 00:35:58.323 align:middle line:10%
it means that for
those several years,

00:35:58.323 --> 00:36:01.570 align:middle line:10%
you'd have major global
agricultural collapses.

00:36:01.570 --> 00:36:04.660 align:middle line:10%
And within two to
three years, people

00:36:04.660 --> 00:36:06.400 align:middle line:10%
would be starving to death.

00:36:06.400 --> 00:36:10.150 align:middle line:10%
And by getting weak
because of hunger,

00:36:10.150 --> 00:36:12.020 align:middle line:10%
their immune systems get weak.

00:36:12.020 --> 00:36:14.830 align:middle line:10%
And that's why you always say
that the ancients have told

00:36:14.830 --> 00:36:16.690 align:middle line:10%
us pestilence follows famine.

00:36:16.690 --> 00:36:20.630 align:middle line:10%
Because pestilence is when you
have weakened immune systems,

00:36:20.630 --> 00:36:23.920 align:middle line:10%
that creates the opportunity
for infectious diseases

00:36:23.920 --> 00:36:25.390 align:middle line:10%
to spread rapidly.

00:36:25.390 --> 00:36:31.130 align:middle line:84%
And so that right there is
about a 2 to 3-degree cooling.

00:36:31.130 --> 00:36:32.910 align:middle line:84%
Actually, maybe even
4 degrees cooling.

00:36:32.910 --> 00:36:34.358 align:middle line:90%
It lasted maybe up to a decade.

00:36:34.358 --> 00:36:35.900 align:middle line:10%
Something like that
would happen now,

00:36:35.900 --> 00:36:38.910 align:middle line:10%
we'd be profoundly stressed.

00:36:38.910 --> 00:36:41.040 align:middle line:10%
But I want you to look at
something when we go back

00:36:41.040 --> 00:36:43.600 align:middle line:10%
into the Pleistocene.

00:36:43.600 --> 00:36:46.215 align:middle line:84%
Here's the same graph, and
I'm going to extend it back.

00:36:46.215 --> 00:36:50.280 align:middle line:90%


00:36:50.280 --> 00:36:55.520 align:middle line:10%
If you tell me that the
climate science has settled,

00:36:55.520 --> 00:36:58.290 align:middle line:10%
I'm going to demand that
you explain this to me.

00:36:58.290 --> 00:37:00.540 align:middle line:10%
This graph right here.

00:37:00.540 --> 00:37:02.730 align:middle line:10%
We're looking at
temperature changes

00:37:02.730 --> 00:37:06.660 align:middle line:10%
of up to 10 and 12
degrees centigrade, which

00:37:06.660 --> 00:37:09.520 align:middle line:10%
is up to 18 degrees
Fahrenheit-- guess what--

00:37:09.520 --> 00:37:12.653 align:middle line:10%
in less than five years, maybe
even less than three years.

00:37:12.653 --> 00:37:14.070 align:middle line:84%
And, in fact, some
of the evidence

00:37:14.070 --> 00:37:16.028 align:middle line:84%
suggests that some of
these temperature changes

00:37:16.028 --> 00:37:19.990 align:middle line:90%
occurred within one year.

00:37:19.990 --> 00:37:23.170 align:middle line:10%
I think it's imperative that we
come to a deeper understanding

00:37:23.170 --> 00:37:25.880 align:middle line:10%
of what's going on here.

00:37:25.880 --> 00:37:29.330 align:middle line:84%
Because this is the record of
the last couple of 100,000 years

00:37:29.330 --> 00:37:30.380 align:middle line:90%
on Earth.

00:37:30.380 --> 00:37:34.900 align:middle line:84%
And this is the world that our
ancestors were surviving in.

00:37:34.900 --> 00:37:37.390 align:middle line:84%
"From measurements of annual
ice-layer thickness over

00:37:37.390 --> 00:37:39.820 align:middle line:84%
the past 15,000 years,
the authors find that

00:37:39.820 --> 00:37:42.490 align:middle line:84%
Greenland's climate, emerging
from the last ice age,

00:37:42.490 --> 00:37:46.660 align:middle line:84%
twice shifted from glacial to
interglacial conditions over

00:37:46.660 --> 00:37:52.120 align:middle line:84%
an astonishingly quick
three to five years."

00:37:52.120 --> 00:37:55.060 align:middle line:10%
And here this is
just a large part

00:37:55.060 --> 00:37:56.770 align:middle line:10%
of the graph we just looked at.

00:37:56.770 --> 00:38:00.010 align:middle line:10%
And you'll see that there are
two shifts to the left are cold,

00:38:00.010 --> 00:38:02.870 align:middle line:10%
shifts to the right are warm.

00:38:02.870 --> 00:38:07.210 align:middle line:10%
You're going to see that we
have two extreme warming events.

00:38:07.210 --> 00:38:11.230 align:middle line:10%
The lower one is meltwater pulse
associated with meltwater pulse

00:38:11.230 --> 00:38:15.580 align:middle line:10%
1B, which is probably related
to something that occurred with

00:38:15.580 --> 00:38:16.520 align:middle line:10%
the sun.

00:38:16.520 --> 00:38:19.720 align:middle line:10%
The second one is
the Younger Dryas.

00:38:19.720 --> 00:38:22.300 align:middle line:10%
Actually, the end
of the Younger Dryas

00:38:22.300 --> 00:38:24.700 align:middle line:10%
and the subsidence
of Plato's Atlantis,

00:38:24.700 --> 00:38:27.050 align:middle line:10%
that second red arrow there.

00:38:27.050 --> 00:38:29.770 align:middle line:10%
And those two
warming events were

00:38:29.770 --> 00:38:35.180 align:middle line:10%
associated with two very rapid
melting of the ice sheets,

00:38:35.180 --> 00:38:38.690 align:middle line:10%
extraordinarily and extreme
catastrophic climatic

00:38:38.690 --> 00:38:41.360 align:middle line:10%
and weather events
that were compressed

00:38:41.360 --> 00:38:44.360 align:middle line:10%
within that narrow
window, which I submit

00:38:44.360 --> 00:38:47.060 align:middle line:10%
led to things like
torrential rain

00:38:47.060 --> 00:38:49.980 align:middle line:10%
falls that might have
lasted for weeks at a time.

00:38:49.980 --> 00:38:54.770 align:middle line:10%
And I've taken many people
out on tours and excursions

00:38:54.770 --> 00:38:57.650 align:middle line:10%
to teach them and show
them, reveal to them

00:38:57.650 --> 00:39:00.800 align:middle line:10%
the evidence of this kind
of events in the landscape

00:39:00.800 --> 00:39:04.350 align:middle line:10%
because the landscapes have
preserved this evidence for us.

00:39:04.350 --> 00:39:05.150 align:middle line:10%
I've gone.

00:39:05.150 --> 00:39:08.630 align:middle line:10%
I've-- in fact, my previous
trips to Las Vegas was because I

00:39:08.630 --> 00:39:11.600 align:middle line:10%
was using Vegas as a jumping off
point to go out, for example,

00:39:11.600 --> 00:39:13.110 align:middle line:10%
into the Mojave Desert.

00:39:13.110 --> 00:39:15.200 align:middle line:10%
And I've taken groups
out there to show

00:39:15.200 --> 00:39:19.070 align:middle line:10%
that the imprint of
gigantic, catastrophic events

00:39:19.070 --> 00:39:22.250 align:middle line:10%
like torrential rain falls,
biblical scale rainfalls,

00:39:22.250 --> 00:39:25.730 align:middle line:10%
have left their imprints in the
deserts of the United States.

